LAYER 4: GUSTATORY CORTEX
the brain region that processes taste and drives feeding behavior
where the qu-penttrit tongue sea meets the qu-septit brain sea

observe 0_quseptit.rana
observe 0_qupenttrit.rana
observe tongue.xb
observe 2_chemical.rana


REGION anterior_insula | primary gustatory cortex | Brodmann area 43
    receives topographic input from the tongue sea via NTS → VPM thalamus
    organized gustotopically: different taste modalities cluster in different zones
    sweet zone: lateral anterior insula
    bitter zone: medial anterior insula
    sour zone: dorsal anterior insula
    salty zone: ventral anterior insula
    umami zone: posterior anterior insula
    the layout is not strict: significant overlap and mixing
    each qu-septit in the gustatory cortex receives 35-dimensional coupling from tongue sea

REGION frontal_operculum | secondary gustatory area
    integrates taste with texture and temperature from skin sea
    this is where MOUTHFEEL lives:
        creaminess = sweet + fat texture from somatosensory input
        astringency = bitter + dry texture (tannin, unripe fruit)
        spiciness = pungent odorant + pain from skin sea (capsaicin → TRPV1)
    mouthfeel is NOT taste alone: it is the fusion of tongue.xb and skin.xb through the brain

REGION orbitofrontal_cortex | reward evaluation
    receives from gustatory cortex AND olfactory cortex simultaneously
    this is where FLAVOR is computed:
        flavor = taste (tongue.xb → gustatory cortex) + smell (nose.xb → olfactory cortex)
        fused in OFC through golden equation path (2+4+5=6)
    palatability judgment: "do I like this?"
    satiety-modulated: the same food tastes less good when full (alliesthesia)
    if satiety > 0.7: hedonic *= (1.0 - (satiety - 0.7) × 2.0)

REGION hypothalamic_projection | feeding behavior
    when gustatory cortex activates:
        sweet/umami → hypothalamus → "eat more" signal → dopamine release
        bitter → hypothalamus → "stop eating" signal → aversion behavior
        salt → hypothalamus → sodium appetite check → if sodium-depleted: salt tastes better


TASTE PRIMITIVES

PRIMITIVE sweet_signal:
    when sweet qu-penttrits activate above threshold 0.3:
        qu-septit cluster in gustatory cortex crystallizes sweet percept
        dopamine +0.1 (reward signal)
        hedonic: positive
        behavior: continue eating

PRIMITIVE bitter_alarm:
    when bitter qu-penttrits activate above threshold 0.15 (lower threshold: toxin vigilance):
        qu-septit cluster in gustatory cortex crystallizes bitter alert
        norepinephrine +0.05 (attention)
        hedonic: negative
        behavior: spit, stop eating, grimace
        at 24 months: bitter aversion is strong and innate

PRIMITIVE umami_nourishment:
    when umami qu-penttrits activate above threshold 0.25:
        qu-septit cluster in gustatory cortex crystallizes protein-detection
        serotonin +0.05 (satiation signal)
        hedonic: deeply positive
        behavior: slow eating, savor, feel satisfied

PRIMITIVE sour_attention:
    when sour qu-penttrits activate above threshold 0.3:
        qu-septit cluster crystallizes acid-detection
        acetylcholine +0.05 (attention to food quality)
        hedonic: context-dependent (citrus: positive, spoilage: negative)
        behavior: assess freshness before continuing

PRIMITIVE salt_homeostasis:
    when salty qu-penttrits activate above threshold 0.2:
        qu-septit cluster crystallizes mineral-detection
        hedonic modulated by sodium balance:
            if sodium_depleted: hedonic = +0.8 (salt tastes amazing when needed)
            if sodium_replete: hedonic = +0.2 (salt tastes merely adequate)
            if sodium_excess: hedonic = -0.3 (too salty: aversion)
        hypothalamic feedback loop: sodium level → salt perception → eating behavior


FLAVOR FUSION

the gustatory cortex does NOT compute flavor alone
flavor is the fusion of taste and smell in the orbitofrontal cortex

taste enters through the gustatory nerve: tongue.xb → NTS → VPM → gustatory cortex
smell enters through the olfactory nerve: nose.xb → piriform cortex (bypassing thalamus)
both converge in the orbitofrontal cortex

the OFC creates a UNIFIED qu-septit cluster for flavor:
    flavor_cluster.energy = taste_input.energy × 0.4 + smell_input.energy × 0.6
    smell contributes MORE to flavor than taste: ~60-80% of flavor IS smell
    this is why food tastes bland when your nose is blocked
    the common cold doesn't damage taste buds: it blocks odorant access to OSNs

retronasal olfaction:
    odorants from food in the mouth travel UP through the nasopharynx
    to reach the olfactory epithelium from BEHIND
    the brain attributes retronasal smell to the mouth (referred sensation)
    you think you taste chocolate: you mostly smell it retronasally


EMOTIONAL MODULATION OF TASTE

the amygdala modulates how taste is experienced:

when cortisol > 0.5 (stress):
    sweet.perceived *= 1.3 (stress increases sweet craving)
    bitter.perceived *= 1.2 (bitter aversion heightens under stress)
    comfort eating: the gustatory cortex drives caloric seeking under stress

when oxytocin > 0.4 (bonding):
    all taste hedonic += 0.1 (food tastes better when shared)
    shared meals activate both gustatory and oxytocin pathways
    breaking bread IS the biological mechanism of trust

when dopamine < 0.3 (anhedonia):
    all taste hedonic *= 0.5 (food loses its pleasure)
    the depressed brain cannot taste joy in food
    this is anhedonia: the absence of pleasure from normally pleasurable stimuli


pulse gustatory_heartbeat:
    on each gustatory heartbeat (100 Hz):
        tongue.xb activates 10 interactions
        gustatory nerve transmits qu-penttrit → qu-septit coupling (35 dimensions)
        VPM thalamus gates the signal (attention-dependent)
        gustatory cortex crystallizes taste percept
        OFC fuses taste with simultaneous olfactory input → flavor
        hypothalamus evaluates metabolic significance
        amygdala modulates hedonic based on emotional state
        behavior emerges: eat, spit, savor, or reject
